     <article>
      <div class="comment by-terry" id="c6690242"> 
       <p class="commentcredit"><span class="commenter">Terry</span> • <a href="https://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2015/02/everyone_wants_.html#c6690242">February 26, 2015 3:51 PM</a> </p> 
       <p>Whitfield Diffie is wrong.</p> 
       <p>The problem of e.g. email attachments is trivial to resolve. You just have to be willing to delay starting to render the contents of an email message until after you have validated the MIME container.</p> 
       <p>This makes email seem slower than it would appear were you to, as Microsoft Outlook has historically done, start immediately interpreting the container contents *as if* they were trustworthy, rather than untrusted.</p> 
       <p>This is one of those cases where the tradeoff between security and convenience is being (wrongheadedly) made in favor of convenience.</p> 
       <p>But it's a solved problem, if we are willing to make the trade the other way.</p> 
      </div>
     </article> 
