      <div class="comment by-nick-p" id="c6690257"> 
       <p class="commentcredit"><span class="commenter">Nick P</span> • <a href="https://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2015/02/everyone_wants_.html#c6690257">February 26, 2015 7:02 PM</a> </p> 
       <p>@ Terry</p> 
       <p>You don't even need to do that: just run the risky components in a dedicated partition on a microkernel architecture. It's one of my oldest recommendations as there was so much work in security and separation kernel architectures. <a href="http://www.perseus-os.org/content/pages/Architecture.htm" rel="nofollow">Example.</a> The TUDOS team at TU-Dresden showed whole VM's could be spawned at a rate of about 1 a second with little overhead. The app's rendering and processing systems would similarly be in a VM whose output was a graphic the system prints in a specific window. Compromises are contained.</p> 
       <p>The signature checking might even run as a background process. </p> 
